                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/13396.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Brazilian Minister</gloss> to Mexico to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Brazilian Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-10-05T11:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 5, 1914, 11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>176. Instead of receiving any reply from Foreign Office to my notes sent as per
                    your No. 252, September 22, 9 p.m., and No. 267, October 1, 7 p.m., the papers
                    to-day announced as reported in official circles that they are going to ask the
                    American Government if order for withdrawal from Vera Cruz is still in force and
                    if so to fix a date on which evacuation will take place.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cardoso de Oliveira</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
